    {
      "id": "522496d903ef4896cdb0f9dbffad3290bb7d27bc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-05-14 00:40:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(2 comments)\n\nJames, it may depend on how the application is linked?  I think I would agree that using .so directly is probably wrong, but may be an artifact of some older packaging of liblustreapi.so without versioning (e.g. before v2_10_56_0-113-g7b659a1e68 \"LU-5541 build: move libcfs and liblustreapi over to libtool\")?  It would be useful to check old lustre RPMs to see when .so.1 was added.\n\nI see recent Lustre utilities are linking to the actual library version:\n$ ldd $(which lfs)\n\tliblustreapi.so.1 => /lib64/liblustreapi.so.1 (0x00007fee991aa000)\n\tliblnetconfig.so.4 => /lib64/liblnetconfig.so.4 (0x00007fee98f86000)\n\nwhich is what I would expect.  Otherwise, if the application uses .so (instead of .so.1) then the application may break if the .so symlink points to .so.2.\n\nThat said, we may need to include the .so symlink into the main package for some versions until older binaries are retired?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5127e7e741d0b1b8bbdea6ae9d65980f9f1456df",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2021-05-14 01:47:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified+1\n\nPassed enforced test review-ldiskfs-dne on CentOS 8.3/x86_64 uploaded by Trevis Autotest 2 from trevis-42vm6: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/ed654e21-c0f4-4d02-8ffb-74d2b4ae6ba7 ran 5 tests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "305e2752ddbc9d9556305ef90d221c73c8c5ddff",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2021-05-14 18:36:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWe have tried our Cray compute nodes with 2.14 for our internal testing and they didn't have the lustre-devel rpms installed. Same for the 2.12 version. We have special libraries that are linked to liblustreapi and we have run latest IOR that links to liblusterapi as well. In all cases the applications always ran with no issues.\n\nI really think this is a case of a HPE utility having a broken build system. Plus as you pointed out linking to *.so is a bad idea if ever the last number changed. Now I do agree liblustreapi linking is a bit fragile. I have played with pkgconf setup for Lustre so projects could use that. It would always provide the correct linking and include paths. \nEven if you someone built lustre with \n\nconfigure --prefix=/my/special/place.\n\nLet me see if I can get cycles to push that work. Note projects would have to use pkg-conf in their builds to take advantage of this. I recommend HPE here to update their build system after such a patch landed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a00ab74fa8b6afb4394027202c18c0596cadc356",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 233,
        "name": "Alexander Zarochentsev",
        "email": "alexander.zarochentsev@hpe.com",
        "username": "zam"
      },
      "date": "2021-05-19 14:44:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nthe utility was built against 2.10 , which has no version for liblustreapi.so.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d6cc6103a51d3dd1eb9a9c7cdedcd2fa299e7cca",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 233,
        "name": "Alexander Zarochentsev",
        "email": "alexander.zarochentsev@hpe.com",
        "username": "zam"
      },
      "date": "2021-05-19 14:47:01.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nit was a compatibility issue with an old app built against lustre-2.10.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f542c61851d127e464b471985aa1b165974c6050",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-05-20 02:41:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI wouldn't necessarily say that an app linked against 2.10 is \"old\" (2.10.8 was released 2019-05-26, so only 2 years ago), so we should really consider whether it makes sense to keep this .so symlink around in the main package for compatibility until at least after 2.15?\n\nJames, beyond making avid readers of the RPM spec unhappy, is there any fallout to keeping the .so symlink in the main lustre.rpm file?  We wouldn't want applications to link against that, but newly linked applications _should_ still use .so.1 if it is available I think?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    }
  ],
